Object — singletons and companions.

An object declares a single instance of a class. There is no constructor, no new keyword needed — the object simply is. You use it for utility methods, configuration, and constants that have no per-instance state.

When an object has the same name as a class in the same file, it is called the companion object of that class. Companion objects are special — they can access the class's private members, and the class can access the object's. This is exactly where you put factory methods and shared utilities.

The most important of those factory methods is apply. The apply method on a companion is the basis of the list-of-one-two-three idiom — writing list with no new keyword is really calling list dot apply. If you define your own apply on a companion, your class gets the same call-site sugar. Picture a money type with a private constructor and a companion object that offers an apply taking dollars and cents, a second factory that builds from raw cents, and a zero constant. Because the companion can see the private constructor, callers get clean factory methods — money of twelve, fifty — and never touch new or the private internals themselves.
